{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772179793738,"sessionID":"ses_361dd9449ffeew5aJsn1EdIX3R","part":{"id":"prt_c9e25a5b9001g8kaEu5OsL30yO","sessionID":"ses_361dd9449ffeew5aJsn1EdIX3R","messageID":"msg_c9e25a1b4001Q9t5wrLr39yRty","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_012yhqveg2PnnMzeB4jX3YzL","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/architecture/overview.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/architecture/overview.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Architecture Overview\n2: \n3: > High-level description of the major domains, module boundaries, and\n4: > cross-domain interaction patterns in the super-ralph agent framework.\n5: \n6: **Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n7: \n8: ## Purpose\n9: \n10: super-ralph is a CLI-driven orchestration framework that coordinates three\n11: external systems — an AI coding agent (opencode), a task tracker (`br`), and\n12: a structured intake methodology (Superpowers) — through a single configurable\n13: runtime loop called the Ralph Loop.\n14: \n15: The framework sits between a human operator and an AI agent. It selects work\n16: items, renders prompts from templates, streams agent execution, and records\n17: results. The agent itself runs inside opencode and has no direct knowledge of\n18: the orchestration layer.\n19: \n20: ## Major Domains\n21: \n22: The nineteen modules in `src/` fall into five domains.\n23: \n24: ### 1. CLI Entry Point\n25: \n26: **Module:** `src/index.ts`\n27: \n28: The CLI entry point parses arguments and dispatches to the appropriate phase\n29: or utility command. It is the single process boundary between the operator and\n30: the framework internals. No business logic lives here; it delegates immediately\n31: to phase or utility functions.\n32: \n33: **Commands dispatched:** `forward`, `decompose`, `reverse`, `init`, `status`,\n34: `doctor`, `help`.\n35: \n36: ### 2. Phases\n37: \n38: **Modules:** `src/forward.ts`, `src/decompose.ts`, `src/reverse.ts`\n39: \n40: Phase modules implement the three top-level workflow commands. Each phase\n41: constructs a `PhaseCallbacks` object (`src/types.ts`) and passes it to the\n42: engine. The three callbacks define phase-specific behavior:\n43: \n44: - `setup` — reads configuration, resolves work items, returns iteration count.\n45: - `nextIteration` — selects the next item and renders a prompt.\n46: - `handleResult` — interprets the agent's completion signal.\n47: \n48: The phases share no code with each other. They are isolated strategy\n49: implementations that plug into the single engine loop.\n50: \n51: | Phase | Input | Output |\n52: | --- | --- | --- |\n53: | `reverse` | Free-text inputs, skill file | Markdown spec file in `docs/specs/` |\n54: | `decompose` | Markdown spec file | beads (tasks) created via `br` CLI |\n55: | `forward` | Epic ID (set of beads) | Committed code changes |\n56: \n57: ### 3. Engine\n58: \n59: **Module:** `src/engine.ts`\n60: \n61: The engine owns the generic select-prompt-execute-evaluate loop. All three\n62: phases use the same `runPhaseLoop` function. The engine is responsible for:\n63: \n64: - Starting or attaching to an opencode server (`src/opencode.ts`).\n65: - Iterating until work is exhausted or a stop condition is reached.\n66: - Applying the configured retry or failure strategy.\n67: - Emitting typed engine events (`src/events.ts`).\n68: - Writing run artifacts via the run tracker (`src/run-state.ts`).\n69: \n70: The engine has no knowledge of beads, spec files, or prompt content. Those\n71: concerns belong entirely to the phase callbacks.\n72: \n73: ### 4. Integrations\n74: \n75: **Modules:** `src/opencode.ts`, `src/interactive.ts`, `src/beads.ts`\n76: \n77: Integration modules wrap external services behind typed interfaces.\n78: \n79: **opencode adapter** (`src/opencode.ts`) manages the full lifecycle of the\n80: opencode server: spawning a process on a random port, creating sessions,\n81: streaming prompt results over Server-Sent Events (SSE), and extracting\n82: completion signals from session message history.\n83: \n84: **Interactive session handler** (`src/interactive.ts`) extends the opencode\n85: adapter for the interactive reverse mode. It intercepts `question.asked` SSE\n86: events and renders them to the terminal using `@clack/prompts`, then sends\n87: the operator's answers back to the agent via `question.reply`.\n88: \n89: **bead integration** (`src/beads.ts`) wraps the `br` CLI. It spawns child\n90: processes, parses JSON output, and returns typed `BeadInfo` objects. The\n91: framework never reads `.beads/` files directly.\n92: \n93: ### 5. Infrastructure\n94: \n95: **Modules:** `src/config.ts`, `src/template.ts`, `src/skills.ts`,\n96: `src/events.ts`, `src/run-state.ts`, `src/run-status.ts`, `src/progress.ts`,\n97: `src/output-parser.ts`, `src/timeout.ts`, `src/init.ts`, `src/types.ts`\n98: \n99: Infrastructure modules provide cross-cutting support consumed by the engine\n100: and phases.\n101: \n102: | Module | Role |\n103: | --- | --- |\n104: | `config.ts` | Loads `.super-ralph/config.toml`, merges defaults, resolves AI models |\n105: | `template.ts` | Loads and renders Handlebars `.hbs` prompt templates |\n106: | `skills.ts` | Resolves skill names to Markdown question-bank content |\n107: | `events.ts` | Defines the engine event union type and a pub/sub emitter |\n108: | `run-state.ts` | Writes per-run artifacts: `session.json`, `events.jsonl`, transcripts |\n109: | `run-status.ts` | Read-only companion: resolves run references and reads artifacts |\n110: | `progress.ts` | Appends and reads Markdown progress summaries per iteration |\n111: | `output-parser.ts` | Captures raw SSE lines and display text during agent sessions |\n112: | `timeout.ts` | Races a promise against a deadline |\n113: | `init.ts` | Scaffolds new projects: directories, templates, opencode plugin |\n114: | `types.ts` | Central type definitions shared across all modules |\n115: \n116: ## Entry Points\n117: \n118: There is one primary entry point and one secondary entry point.\n119: \n120: **Primary:** `src/index.ts` — invoked by the shell wrapper installed by\n121: `install.sh`. The wrapper calls `bun run ~/.super-ralph-cli/src/index.ts \"$@\"`.\n122: \n123: **Secondary:** `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js` — loaded by the opencode\n124: server at startup. This plugin registers the `task_complete` tool that agents\n125: call to signal iteration completion. It is not invoked by the operator.\n126: \n127: ## Cross-Domain Interaction Boundaries\n128: \n129: ### CLI to Phase\n130: \n131: `src/index.ts` calls a command function in the phase module (for example,\n132: `cmdForward` in `src/forward.ts`). The call transfers control entirely;\n133: `index.ts` only inspects the returned `LoopResult` to set the process exit\n134: code.\n135: \n136: ### Phase to Engine\n137: \n138: Each phase constructs a `PhaseCallbacks` literal and calls\n139: `runPhaseLoop(projectDir, callbacks, flags)` from `src/engine.ts`. The engine\n140: invokes the callbacks at defined points in the loop. This is the only\n141: coupling between phase modules and the engine.\n142: \n143: ### Engine to opencode Adapter\n144: \n145: The engine calls `startServer()` or `connectToServer()`, then\n146: `createSession(client, title)` and `runPrompt(...)` from `src/opencode.ts`.\n147: The adapter returns a `PromptResult` containing the agent's completion signal,\n148: cost metadata, and token counts.\n149: \n150: ### Engine to bead Integration\n151: \n152: Phase callbacks call functions from `src/beads.ts` (such as `getAllReady`,\n153: `getBeadDetails`, `runBr`) to read and update task state. The engine itself\n154: does not call `src/beads.ts` directly; only phase callbacks do.\n155: \n156: ### Agent to Orchestrator (task\\_complete plugin)\n157: \n158: The agent running inside opencode signals completion by calling the\n159: `task_complete` tool registered by `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js`. After\n160: the agent session becomes idle, the engine scans `session.messages()` for a\n161: `task_complete` tool-call result. This is the only channel through which the\n162: agent communicates its outcome to the orchestrator.\n163: \n164: ### Phase to Phase (filesystem)\n165: \n166: The three phases communicate only through the filesystem and the `br` CLI.\n167: There is no direct function call or shared in-process state between phases.\n168: \n169: ```text\n170: reverse   -->  writes Markdown spec  -->  docs/specs/<name>.md\n171: decompose -->  reads spec, writes beads via br  -->  .beads/\n172: forward   -->  reads beads via br, writes code  -->  project source files\n173: ```\n174: \n175: ### Engine to Run Artifacts\n176: \n177: After each iteration the engine writes to `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/` via\n178: `src/run-state.ts`. It also appends to `.super-ralph/progress.md` via\n179: `src/progress.ts`. These files are read back by the `status` command and,\n180: in the forward phase, by the agent as prior-iteration context.\n181: \n182: ## Configuration Boundary\n183: \n184: Configuration is loaded once per run by `loadConfig(projectDir)` in\n185: `src/config.ts`. The resulting `LoopConfig` object is passed through\n186: `runPhaseLoop` to callbacks and adapter functions. No module reads\n187: `config.toml` directly except `src/config.ts`.\n188: \n189: ## Filesystem Layout (per project)\n190: \n191: After `super-ralph init`, a project contains the following framework-managed\n192: directories:\n193: \n194: ```text\n195: <project-root>/\n196:   .super-ralph/\n197:     config.toml          # Runtime configuration\n198:     *.hbs                # Customizable prompt templates\n199:     intake-checklist.md  # Accumulated intake questions\n200:     progress.md          # Per-iteration progress log (runtime)\n201:     session.json         # Live run state mirror (runtime)\n202:     runs/\n203:       <runId>/\n204:         session.json     # Run summary\n205:         events.jsonl     # Structured event log\n206:         iterations/\n207:           001-<label>.log\n208:   .opencode/\n209:     plugins/\n210:       super-ralph.js     # task_complete tool plugin\n211:   .beads/                # Managed by br CLI\n212:   docs/specs/            # Spec files from reverse phase (default location)\n213: ```\n214: \n215: ## Open Questions\n216: \n217: - The `--attach <url>` flag mode is confirmed in `src/engine.ts` and\n218:   `src/opencode.ts`, but the behavior when the attached server shuts down\n219:   externally is not fully characterized. [UNKNOWN]\n\n(End of file - total 219 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/architecture/overview.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Architecture Overview\n\n> High-level description of the major domains, module boundaries, and\n> cross-domain interaction patterns in the super-ralph agent framework.\n\n**Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n\n## Purpose\n\nsuper-ralph is a CLI-driven orchestration framework that coordinates three\nexternal systems — an AI coding agent (opencode), a task tracker (`br`), and\na structured intake methodology (Superpowers) — through a single configurable\nruntime loop called the Ralph Loop.\n\nThe framework sits between a human operator and an AI agent. It selects work\nitems, renders prompts from templates, streams agent execution, and records\nresults. The agent itself runs inside opencode and has no direct knowledge of\nthe orchestration layer.\n\n## Major Domains","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772179793733,"end":1772179793737}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1772179794122,"sessionID":"ses_361dd9449ffeew5aJsn1EdIX3R","part":{"id":"prt_c9e25a746001MSABy7AVP9SUMC","sessionID":"ses_361dd9449ffeew5aJsn1EdIX3R","messageID":"msg_c9e25a1b4001Q9t5wrLr39yRty","type":"tool","callID":"toolu_01PDb9iQfUX7YZv4eiTKC6Ew","tool":"read","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/mat/dev/farsight/agent-framework/spec/architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>1: # Runtime Lifecycle\n2: \n3: > Description of how super-ralph initializes, executes the steady-state loop,\n4: > and shuts down for each phase invocation.\n5: \n6: **Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n7: \n8: ## Overview\n9: \n10: Every phase invocation (`reverse`, `decompose`, `forward`) follows the same\n11: runtime lifecycle managed by `runPhaseLoop` in `src/engine.ts`. The lifecycle\n12: has three stages:\n13: \n14: 1. **Initialization** — load configuration, create run artifacts, start server.\n15: 2. **Steady-state loop** — iterate: select, prompt, execute, evaluate.\n16: 3. **Shutdown** — finalize artifacts, close server, detach listeners.\n17: \n18: The lifecycle is the same regardless of which phase runs. Phase-specific\n19: behavior is injected through the `PhaseCallbacks` interface\n20: (`src/engine.ts:18`).\n21: \n22: ---\n23: \n24: ## Stage 1: Initialization\n25: \n26: ### 1.1 CLI Dispatch\n27: \n28: The operator invokes `super-ralph <phase> [flags]`. The shell wrapper calls\n29: `bun run src/index.ts \"$@\"`. Argument parsing in `src/index.ts` produces a\n30: `ParsedArgs` object (`command`, `positionals`, `flags`). Control transfers\n31: to the phase command function (e.g., `cmdForward` in `src/forward.ts`).\n32: \n33: ### 1.2 Phase Setup\n34: \n35: The phase command function calls `runPhaseLoop(projectDir, callbacks, flags)`.\n36: \n37: Inside `runPhaseLoop` (`src/engine.ts:24`):\n38: \n39: 1. An `EngineEventEmitter` is created (`src/engine.ts:30`).\n40: 2. A console renderer is attached (`attachDefaultConsoleRenderer`,\n41:    `src/engine.ts:31`). This listener writes events to stdout.\n42: 3. An optional external listener is attached if `onEvent` is provided\n43:    (`src/engine.ts:32`). Used for testing and TUI integration.\n44: 4. Configuration is loaded: `loadConfig(projectDir)` (`src/engine.ts:44`).\n45:    This reads `.super-ralph/config.toml`, merges defaults, and returns a\n46:    `LoopConfig` object.\n47: 5. `callbacks.setup(config, dryRun)` is called (`src/engine.ts:46`). The\n48:    phase determines `maxIterations` and `description`.\n49: 6. A `RunTracker` is created: `startRunTracker(projectDir, description,\n50:    maxIterations)` (`src/engine.ts:48`). This creates the run directory at\n51:    `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/` and writes an initial `session.json`.\n52: 7. The tracker's event listener is attached (`src/engine.ts:49`).\n53: \n54: ### 1.3 Server Start\n55: \n56: If `flags.dryRun` is set, server startup is skipped entirely\n57: (`src/engine.ts:55`).\n58: \n59: Otherwise:\n60: \n61: - If `flags.attach` is set: `connectToServer(url)` wraps an existing\n62:   opencode server (`src/engine.ts:80`). The `server.attached` event is\n63:   emitted.\n64: - Otherwise: `startServer()` spawns a new opencode process on a random\n65:   port (`src/engine.ts:83`). The `server.started` and `server.attach_hint`\n66:   events are emitted.\n67: \n68: `startServer` is implemented in `src/opencode.ts`. It calls\n69: `createOpencode({ port: 0 })` from the opencode SDK, then verifies the server\n70: is responsive by calling `client.session.list()`.\n71: \n72: ---\n73: \n74: ## Stage 2: Steady-State Loop\n75: \n76: The main loop runs while `iteration < maxIterations` (`src/engine.ts:96`).\n77: \n78: ### 2.1 Work Selection\n79: \n80: `callbacks.nextIteration(config, iteration + 1)` is called\n81: (`src/engine.ts:97`). The phase implementation selects the next unit of work\n82: and returns a `PhaseIteration` object containing:\n83: \n84: - `prompt` — the rendered Handlebars template.\n85: - `model` — resolved `{ providerID, modelID }`.\n86: - `sessionTitle` — displayed in the opencode session list.\n87: - `iterationLabel` — used for transcript filenames and event labels.\n88: - `beadId` (optional) — the bead being worked on.\n89: - `systemPrompt` (optional) — injected as the system message.\n90: \n91: If `nextIteration` returns `null`, the loop exits (`src/engine.ts:98`). This\n92: is the normal termination path: no more work remains.\n93: \n94: ### 2.2 Session Creation\n95: \n96: `createSession(server.client, sessionTitle)` creates a new opencode session\n97: (`src/engine.ts:112`). Each iteration gets a fresh context window; no session\n98: state carries over between iterations.\n99: \n100: ### 2.3 Prompt Execution\n101: \n102: `runPrompt(client, sessionId, prompt, model, systemPrompt, serverUrl,\n103: inactivityTimeoutMs)` is called inside `withTimeout(...)` (`src/engine.ts:\n104: 117`). Two timeout guards are active simultaneously:\n105: \n106: - **Hard timeout:** `withTimeout` rejects after\n107:   `config.engine.timeout_minutes * 60 * 1000` milliseconds (`src/engine.ts:\n108:   115`). This is an absolute wall-clock limit per iteration.\n109: - **Inactivity timeout:** Inside `runPrompt`, a watchdog fires every ten\n110:   seconds. If no SSE event has arrived for\n111:   `config.engine.inactivity_timeout_seconds` seconds, the session is aborted\n112:   (`src/opencode.ts`).\n113: \n114: `runPrompt` opens an SSE event stream via the opencode SDK v2 client, sends\n115: the prompt, and processes events until the session becomes idle:\n116: \n117: - `message.part.delta` — streams text to stdout via `StreamCapture`.\n118: - `message.part.updated` — displays tool-call status lines.\n119: - `session.idle` — normal completion; exits the event loop.\n120: - `session.error` — error completion; exits the event loop.\n121: \n122: After the event loop exits, `runPrompt` reads `session.messages()` to locate\n123: the `task_complete` tool-call result. This becomes the `CompletionResult`\n124: (`status`, `reason`). Cost and token metadata are also extracted.\n125: \n126: `runPrompt` returns a `PromptResult` (`src/opencode.ts`).\n127: \n128: ### 2.4 Artifact Recording\n129: \n130: After `runPrompt` returns (`src/engine.ts:138`):\n131: \n132: 1. `runTracker.writeIterationTranscript(...)` writes raw SSE lines and\n133:    display text to `.super-ralph/runs/<runId>/iterations/<N>-<label>.log`.\n134: 2. `appendProgress(projectDir, iteration, iterResult)` appends a summary\n135:    entry to `.super-ralph/progress.md`.\n136: \n137: ### 2.5 Result Evaluation\n138: \n139: `callbacks.handleResult(result, iteration)` is called (`src/engine.ts:151`).\n140: The phase returns `true` to continue or `false` to stop the loop.\n141: \n142: The engine then applies the result status:\n143: \n144: | Status | Counter | Action |\n145: | --- | --- | --- |\n146: | `complete` or `phase_done` | `completed++` | emit `iteration.completed`, continue |\n147: | `blocked` | `skipped++` | emit `iteration.blocked`, continue |\n148: | `failed`, `stalled`, `timeout`, `error` | see below | apply strategy |\n149: \n150: **Failure strategy** (`src/engine.ts:172`):\n151: \n152: - `retry` (default): if `retryCount < config.engine.max_retries`, decrement\n153:   `iteration` and re-run the same work item on the next pass. Retry counts\n154:   are tracked per `iterationLabel`.\n155: - `abort`: increment `failed`, emit `iteration.failed` with\n156:   `action: \"aborting\"`, break the loop.\n157: - `skip`: increment `failed`, emit `iteration.failed` with\n158:   `action: \"skipping\"`, continue to the next item.\n159: \n160: If `handleResult` returned `false`, the loop exits after applying the result\n161: (`src/engine.ts:206`).\n162: \n163: ### 2.6 Inter-iteration Delay\n164: \n165: If `config.engine.iteration_delay_ms > 0`, the engine sleeps before the next\n166: iteration (`src/engine.ts:231`). Default is 2000 ms.\n167: \n168: ---\n169: \n170: ## Primary Runtime Path: Sequence Diagram\n171: \n172: The following diagram shows a single successful iteration in the forward phase.\n173: Steady-state loops repeat steps 3 through 12 until no beads remain.\n174: \n175: ```text\n176: Operator         index.ts         engine.ts        opencode.ts        br CLI\n177:    |                |                 |                  |               |\n178:    |-- super-ralph forward ---------->|                  |               |\n179:    |                |-- cmdForward -->|                  |               |\n180:    |                |                |-- loadConfig ---->|               |\n181:    |                |                |-- setup() ------->|               |\n182:    |                |                |  [callbacks.setup calls br ready] |\n183:    |                |                |<-----------------------------------br ready\n184:    |                |                |-- startServer() ->|               |\n185:    |                |                |<-- ServerHandle --|               |\n186:    |                |                |                  |               |\n187:    |             [loop begins]       |                  |               |\n188:    |                |                |-- nextIteration()->              |\n189:    |                |                |  [calls br ready, br show]       |\n190:    |                |                |<---------------------------------br\n191:    |                |                |-- createSession()->|             |\n192:    |                |                |<-- sessionId ------|             |\n193:    |                |                |-- runPrompt() ---->|             |\n194:    |                |                |  [SSE stream open] |             |\n195:    |<-- text output ----------------[streaming text]------             |\n196:    |                |                |  [session.idle]    |             |\n197:    |                |                |-- session.messages()-->|         |\n198:    |                |                |<-- task_complete result          |\n199:    |                |                |-- writeTranscript()              |\n200:    |                |                |-- appendProgress()               |\n201:    |                |                |-- handleResult()  |             |\n202:    |             [loop repeats or exits]                 |             |\n203:    |                |                |-- loop.completed  |             |\n204:    |                |                |-- finalize()      |             |\n205:    |                |                |-- server.close() ->|            |\n206:    |<-- exit code --|                |                  |              |\n207: ```\n208: \n209: ---\n210: \n211: ## Stage 3: Shutdown\n212: \n213: Shutdown is handled in the `finally` block of `runPhaseLoop`\n214: (`src/engine.ts:248`).\n215: \n216: ### 3.1 Normal Shutdown\n217: \n218: After the loop exits or `nextIteration` returns `null`:\n219: \n220: 1. The `loop.completed` event is emitted with totals (`src/engine.ts:236`).\n221: 2. `runTracker.finalize(\"completed\")` or `runTracker.finalize(\"failed\")` is\n222:    called depending on whether `failed > 0` (`src/engine.ts:244`).\n223: 3. The `finally` block runs: the tracker listener is detached\n224:    (`src/engine.ts:249`), and `cleanup()` closes the server and detaches\n225:    console and external listeners (`src/engine.ts:36`).\n226: \n227: ### 3.2 Error Shutdown\n228: \n229: If an uncaught exception exits the `try` block before `finalize` is called,\n230: the `finally` block checks `!finalized` and calls\n231: `runTracker.finalize(\"failed\")` (`src/engine.ts:250`). The server is always\n232: closed in `cleanup()`.\n233: \n234: ### 3.3 Dry-Run Shutdown\n235: \n236: In dry-run mode, the engine iterates `nextIteration` without executing\n237: prompts, emits `loop.dry_run_iteration` per item, then calls\n238: `runTracker.finalize(\"completed\")` and returns early (`src/engine.ts:74`).\n239: The server is never started. The `finally` block still runs to detach\n240: listeners.\n241: \n242: ### 3.4 Exit Code\n243: \n244: `runPhaseLoop` returns a `LoopResult`. If `result.failed > 0`, the phase\n245: command function calls `process.exit(1)` (`src/index.ts`).\n246: \n247: ---\n248: \n249: ## Initialization Sequence: super-ralph init\n250: \n251: `super-ralph init` has a different lifecycle from phase commands. It does not\n252: run a loop. `runInit(projectDir)` in `src/init.ts`:\n253: \n254: 1. Creates `.super-ralph/` directory.\n255: 2. Copies five template files from the CLI's `templates/` directory, skipping\n256:    any that already exist.\n257: 3. Writes `.super-ralph/config.toml` with auto-detected `cli.path`.\n258: 4. Installs `.opencode/plugins/super-ralph.js` (the `task_complete` plugin)\n259:    and runs `bun install` in `.opencode/`.\n260: 5. Creates `tasks/` directory.\n261: 6. Runs `br init` if `.beads/` does not exist.\n262: 7. Creates or appends to `AGENTS.md` to reference `.super-ralph/AGENTS.md`.\n263: \n264: `init` does not start an opencode server and writes no run artifacts.\n265: \n266: ---\n267: \n268: ## Configuration Values That Govern Lifecycle\n269: \n270: All values are loaded from `.super-ralph/config.toml` via `src/config.ts`.\n271: \n272: | Key | Default | Effect |\n273: | --- | --- | --- |\n274: | `engine.timeout_minutes` | 30 | Hard wall-clock limit per iteration |\n275: | `engine.inactivity_timeout_seconds` | 180 | Max seconds with no SSE events |\n276: | `engine.iteration_delay_ms` | 2000 | Sleep between iterations |\n277: | `engine.strategy` | `retry` | Failure handling: `retry`, `skip`, or `abort` |\n278: | `engine.max_retries` | 3 | Maximum retries per item when `strategy=retry` |\n279: \n280: ---\n281: \n282: ## Open Questions\n283: \n284: - The behavior when `connectToServer` is called with a URL pointing to a\n285:   server that goes offline mid-run is not fully characterized. [UNKNOWN]\n286: - Whether `session.abort()` in `src/opencode.ts` is reliably honored by the\n287:   opencode SDK during inactivity timeout is not confirmed. [INFERRED]\n\n(End of file - total 287 lines)\n</content>","title":"spec/architecture/runtime-lifecycle.md","metadata":{"preview":"# Runtime Lifecycle\n\n> Description of how super-ralph initializes, executes the steady-state loop,\n> and shuts down for each phase invocation.\n\n**Source examined at commit:** `ecc95c0` (2026-02-27)\n\n## Overview\n\nEvery phase invocation (`reverse`, `decompose`, `forward`) follows the same\nruntime lifecycle managed by `runPhaseLoop` in `src/engine.ts`. The lifecycle\nhas three stages:\n\n1. **Initialization** — load configuration, create run artifacts, start server.\n2. **Steady-state loop** — iterate: select, prompt, execute, evaluate.\n3. **Shutdown** — finalize artifacts, close server, detach listeners.\n\nThe lifecycle is the same regardless of which phase runs. Phase-specific\nbehavior is injected through the `PhaseCallbacks` interface\n(`src/engine.ts:18`).","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"time":{"start":1772179794117,"end":1772179794121}}}}
